Fixed in 3 locations in blockToStep.ts: 1) controls_for block (~line 183), 2) variables_set block (~line 235), 3) convertExpressionToPython helper for variables_get (~line 277). The pattern is: const varId = block.getFieldValue('VAR'); const varModel = block.workspace.getVariableById(varId); const varName = varModel ? varModel.getName() : 'i';
Exported Python code contains corrupted variable names like 'N%hHHhp:Bg=T0!BWtnrB = 0' and 'o(s_~?vBNu5x*!/I9Y1! = (1 + (N%hHHhp:Bg=T0!BWtnrB * 0.5))' instead of 'i' and 'voltage'.
Blockly stores variables with a unique ID (e.g., 'N%hHHhp:Bg=T0!BWtnrB') and a display name (e.g., 'i'). block.getFieldValue('VAR') returns the ID, not the name. The converter was using the ID directly as the Python variable name.
Use Blockly's IVariableModel API: get the variable ID from getFieldValue('VAR'), then resolve the actual name via block.workspace.getVariableById(varId).getName().
// WRONG ❌
const varName = block.getFieldValue('VAR');
// Returns: 'N%hHHhp:Bg=T0!BWtnrB'
// CORRECT ✅
const varId = block.getFieldValue('VAR');
const varModel = block.workspace.getVariableById(varId);
const varName = varModel ? varModel.getName() : 'i';
// Returns: 'i'

Each scpi_write, scpi_query, and similar block has a DEVICE_CONTEXT field (e.g., '(scope)' or '(smu)'). Previously this was treated as a hint while the generator tried to walk the block chain. Now it is authoritative. This means blocks inside loops, conditionals, or any nested structure always know their target device regardless of block chain topology.
SCPI commands inside loops are sent to the wrong device. For example, scope commands inside a loop are generated with SMU context, or all commands default to the last-connected device.
The generator traced device context by walking the block chain via getPreviousBlock(). Inside loops, this chain breaks — the generator can't walk past the loop boundary to find the enclosing device context. It falls through to a wrong currentDeviceContext default.
Make the DEVICE_CONTEXT field on each block the absolute priority for determining which device a command targets. Only fall back to chain-walking if DEVICE_CONTEXT is not set.
// Walked block chain - breaks inside loops
let ctx = block.getPreviousBlock();
while (ctx && ctx.type !== 'set_device_context') {
  ctx = ctx.getPreviousBlock();
}
// Falls through to wrong default
// DEVICE_CONTEXT field is authoritative
const deviceCtx = block.getFieldValue('DEVICE_CONTEXT');
if (deviceCtx) {
  device = resolveDevice(deviceCtx);
} else {
  // Fallback to chain walking only if field not set
}

